**Motivation/Problem**: Studies have made great headway into 3D human pose estimation in controlled environments but there is a lack of literature in estimating pose in uncontrolled environments, which real real-world and safety-critical applications like AV require.

​		Overview of HUM3DIL architecture. It estimates the 3D joint positions of a single person from a multi-modal input representation. We encode LiDAR points P through a Random Fourier Embedding, to produce representations P˜. The LiDAR points are also used to compute a depth-map representation D, which are concatenated with input RGB image I. We first use an image feature extractor (U-Net) that will act on the concatenation of D and I. The projected LiDAR points will further read features from the produced map F. We construct a token sequence of size equal to the number of points. Each token, in the beginning, will have information relating to the image features, camera intrinsics and Random Fourier Embeddings. L sequences of Transformer Encoder will act on the tokens. We read the final Nj tokens and regress the 3D joints through an MLP.
